posts.name: Ryan Blue
posts.cooked:
We use these:

https://www.digikey.com/en/products/detail/molex/0050579403/115034

https://www.digikey.com/en/products/detail/molex/0701070002/210969

They take the standard “molex PWM” contacts and fit into the roborio PWM ports for backwards compatibility. They are keyed so you literally cant connect them backwards. They lock as well. We’ve run them since 2017 and have had no issues so long as they are crimped and strain relieved properly.

In emergency situations we use wago lever nuts but repair when possible.

posts.name: Allen Nuttle
posts.cooked: My personal recommendation is solder and heatshrink when you have the time, with WAGO connectors for quick repairs.  WAGO is an option everywhere, but my own sense of things is the overall reliability may suffer over solder/heatshrink – provided someone has good soldering skills and exercises care in the electrical construction.  Be sure the WAGO connectors you choose are rated for the smaller wire sizes used with CAN, such as these .

posts.name: Mykah
posts.cooked:
3468 has always done a bus configuration and this year is trying out these lever-nut style T-connectors.

Feature: 1. Pure copper electrical conductor has good electrical conductivity, low resistivity, electroplated surface to prevent oxidation. 2. The housing is made of flame retardant insulated material, long life,...

Previously we used these crimp-on T-Connectors along with these crimp-on disconnects.

Wire Connectors - TYUMEN 12pcs 2 Pin 2 Way Low Voltage Universal Compact Wire T Tap Connectors, No Wire-Stripping Required, Toolless Wire Connectors, Quick Splice Wire Wiring Connector for AWG 20-24No need to strip...

Pluggable LED Wire Connectors, TYUMEN 24pcs 2 Pin 2 Way Universal Compact Wire Terminals, No Wire-Stripping Required, Toolless Spring Wire Connectors, Quick Splice Wire Wiring Connector for AWG 20-24No need to strip...

The Crimp-On connectors worked great for us, but I was always a bit worried about the “what if” of a bad crimp, and how hard it would be to diagnose if one happened. The Connectors were also a bit… choosy about what thickness of insulation wire they would work with… The Lever-Nut style ones have the downside of requiring you to cut the “bus” at each connector, but they are easier to add in and you are less prone to bad connections. Both of these solutions have the advantage, to me, over a daisy chain of being able to remove a device from the bus without having to ever break the bus. The crimp-on connectors have the advantage of also not having to break the bus to ADD a device.

posts.name: Dr.G
posts.cooked:
We field tested using a CAN Bus configuration where a CAN wire is attached to the RoboRIO and the other end to the Power Distribution Panel CAN ports. Each CAN device was connected to the bus using a T connector image 679×679 53.2 KB (see https://www.amazon.ca/Kalolary-Connectors-Electrical-Connection-Self-Stripping/dp/B07GXJ46K7/ref=asc_df_B07GXJ46K7/ ).

image 679×679 53.2 KB

image 679×679 53.2 KB

My question is this.

What do we do with the second set of CAN wires?

Could/should we safely cut one set and use the other? Is this advised?

Is there still a likelihood of needing to connect CAN devices in series rather than in parallel ? The latter, essentially, is what we get when using a CANBus with T connectors.

posts.name: Peter Johnson
posts.cooked:
CAN isn’t really serial or parallel, it’s designed to be a multi-drop bus and allows stubs at each drop.  The two sets of CAN wires coming out of the motor controller are directly wired together (literally both ends soldered to the same pad inside the motor controller) so is effectively a “T” junction inside the motor controller with a very short stub (to the motor controller internals).

So it’s safe to cut one set, and if you’re not using it, you should for signal integrity reasons (because otherwise you have a much longer stub that doesn’t go anywhere).
